This scenario is the `err` parameter name, as seen in callbacks:

    doSomething(function (err) {
      doSomethingElse(function (err) {
        // ...
      });
    });

Here, the `no-shadow` rule complains about the second `err` shadowing the first one, but IMHO this is perfectly fine and common in Node.js programming.

